4. Team dashboard (bird's-eye view)
Main page shows:

Total applications, accepted count, in-progress count, critical and not-yet-applied count
Upcoming deadlines in the next 14 days (highlighted in red if within 7 days)
Each team member as a card. Click to expand and see their assigned action items and outreach contacts.
Recent activity feed (last 10 changes across the platform)

5. AI assistant
A chat input in the corner. Connected to the Anthropic Claude API (claude-sonnet-4-20250514). The user types natural language like "mark ESA Kick-starts as submitted" or "what is Abigail working on this week" or "add a new contact: Roberto, Italy, space ecosystem, warm" and the assistant reads the current Supabase state and makes the appropriate update or returns the answer.

Design principles
Simple, dark, and spacious. IOLA brand colors: teal (#00897B) as accent, deep navy (#0D1B2A) as background, amber (#F59E0B) for urgent items. No clutter. Everything readable at a glance. Mobile-friendly. If you click on a team member you expand into their view. No cramped CRM feeling. Every screen has one job.

Supabase tables needed
users (managed by Supabase Auth), applications (all fields above), outreach (all fields above), action_items (all fields above), activity_log (user_id, action, timestamp, entity_type, entity_id).

Auth flow
Jason creates accounts via Supabase admin and sends invite emails. Team members set their own passwords. No public signup. Everyone sees the shared dashboard. Only Jason can delete records or change other users' passwords.

Hosting
Vercel. Connect the GitHub repo iola-tracking-internal. Auto-deploy on push to main.

1. All data is Supabase records, not hardcoded. The pre-populated entries I listed are seed data — they go into a database migration or seed file so Supabase inserts them on first setup. Every single field is editable through the UI. This is a full CRUD application. Create, read, update, delete on every table, every row, every field. Nothing is hardcoded in the frontend.
2. AI assistant uses Gemini, not Claude. Use Google Gemini API (gemini-2.0-flash is fast and cheap). Same concept: natural language input, reads Supabase state, makes updates or answers questions. Gemini's API is straightforward and the free tier is generous enough for internal team use.
Updated applications table fields (replacing what I had before):

id
name (venture or program name)
type (Accelerator / Grant / VC / Angel / Partnership / Academic)
location / region
fund description (what they fund, their thesis, what they look for)
application status (Not Yet Applied / Applied / In Progress / Accepted / Rejected / Pending)
priority level (Critical / High / Medium / Low)
next step (the specific action needed right now)
extra notes (anything else relevant)
amount (funding amount or range)
deadline
contact name
owner (team member)
created_at
updated_at

Everything in that table is editable inline from the dashboard or via a form modal. Status and priority are dropdowns. All other fields are text inputs. Changes write directly to Supabase and update the UI instantly. The activity log records every change with who made it and when.